# Business-context comments (backend)

## Goal

Comments should explain **business intent and invariants** so future changes don’t break product rules. Avoid narrating obvious code mechanics.

## When to add a business comment

- **Cross-cutting behaviors**: transactional boundaries, idempotency, concurrency, rate limits
- **Business invariants**: “draft can be edited”, “sent is immutable”, “user can only access own data”
- **Non-obvious decisions**: why a guard exists, why a fallback is chosen, why a field is derived
- **External contracts**: API behavior guarantees, integration expectations, backwards-compat commitments

## What a good business comment contains

- **Business outcome**: what user/stakeholder goal this supports
- **Invariant(s)**: what must always be true after the function/operation
- **Why**: the risk being prevented (data integrity, reporting accuracy, billing impact, abuse prevention)
- **Scope**: where it applies (route/service/repo), not implementation steps

## Where to place it (layering)

- `routes/`: minimal; only note **public API contract** or major middleware rationale
- `controllers/`: note **input/output shaping** decisions and user-facing behavior (no DB details)
- `services/`: primary place for business comments (rules, invariants, orchestration, transactions)
- `repos/`: explain **data correctness** assumptions (locks, uniqueness, soft-delete semantics), not SQL syntax

## Examples

```ts
// GOOD: explains business invariant + why
/** Send now: mark recipients and campaign in one transaction so the UI never shows "sent" while recipients are still pending. */
export async function sendCampaign(...) { ... }

// BAD: narrates mechanics
// Update recipients then update campaign status.
```

```ts
// GOOD: explains policy
/** Only draft campaigns are editable to preserve reporting/audit integrity once a campaign is scheduled or sent. */
export async function updateCampaignDraft(...) { ... }
```

## Style

- Prefer **1–3 sentences**, focused and concrete
- Avoid copying variable names; talk in **domain language** (user, campaign, recipient, invoice, etc.)
- Never include secrets, stack traces, tokens, or raw request bodies in comments
